   {:e #blake3 "25c93b2e4c7393a02ef78089ae7cd4c93aff6c2209e6fac0d7dfbccdd4f8f438" :a :session/task :v "## Session Synthesis Directive\n\n**Unresolved questions** (carry forward to next session):\n- ASSESSMENT RISK: Single-Customer Overfitting — Risk 2. 46 sessions of DDIS-on-DDIS have optimized the system for one domain: software specification verification. The policy manifest architecture (C8) is architecturally clean — policy.rs uses general-purpose boundary patterns, no hardcoded methodology. But the implementations — harvest pipeline, seed assembly, concept clustering, routing — have all been tuned via 46 sessions of feedback on INV/ADR/NEG ontologies. The DOGFOOD-2 score of 3.48/10 on a Go CLI project is the empirical signal: the universal substrate may have quietly become a DDIS substrate despite clean architectural separation. The risk is that C8 compliance is de jure (architecture clean) but not de facto (implementations tuned to one customer). MITIGATION: Priority 4 (S0-CLOSE external validation) directly tests this. If the system can manage a non-DDIS project (React, research, compliance) with harvest/seed scoring ≥ 7/10, the substrate is genuinely universal. If it scores < 5/10, the substrate/application boundary needs recalibration. Key diagnostic: which seed sections are useful for external projects? Which are DDIS-specific noise? VERIFICATION: Run S0-CLOSE validation on 2+ non-DDIS projects. Compare seed quality, concept relevance, and guidance utility across domains. INTERACTS WITH: S0-CLOSE proposal, concept collapse (hash embedder tuned to DDIS vocabulary), seed assembly (relevance scoring tuned to spec entities). TRACES TO: C8 (substrate independence), ADR-FOUNDATION-012 (epistemology runtime).\n- ASSESSMENT RISK: Daemon May Be a Distraction — Risk 4. Phase E (Active Runtime) requires a session daemon for continuous observation. ADR-STORE-006 was revised in Session 032 from Embedded to Embedded + Session Daemon (Unix socket, W_α, lazy F(S)). DAEMON EPIC was created with 8 tasks (DAEMON-1..6, TEST, E2E). However, the CLI architecture may be sufficient for the core value proposition (harvest/seed lifecycle). If the daemon is necessary for convergence but the CLI can't deliver a proof-of-concept without it, the project has a chicken-and-egg problem. If the CLI CAN deliver the proof-of-concept, the daemon becomes an optimization rather than a prerequisite. The 97s→3s performance fix (Session 039, LiveStore architecture) already removed the primary performance motivation for a daemon. Current braid status runs in ~3s, which is acceptable for CLI-driven workflow. MITIGATION: Validate S0 with CLI first (Priority 4). Only build the daemon if the CLI validates the core hypothesis but demonstrates clear performance/automation bottlenecks that require continuous operation. Do not invest in daemon infrastructure until the CLI proves the concept works. VERIFICATION: S0-CLOSE validation score on CLI-only workflow. If ≥ 7/10 → daemon is optimization, defer to Phase E. If < 5/10 AND the cause is context staleness between commands → daemon may be prerequisite. INTERACTS WITH: S0-CLOSE proposal (determines whether daemon is needed), PERF-REGRESSION epic (daemon was partially motivated by performance), scope creep (daemon work would be premature Phase E). TRACES TO: ADR-STORE-006, Phase E roadmap.\n- ASSESSMENT FINDING: Saw-tooth Convergence Model Not Observable — The saw-tooth invariant predicts F(S) oscillation: spec growth (surprise) causes dip, verification (consolidation) causes recovery. After 13 sessions at F(S) 0.62 ± 0.02, we see neither dip nor recovery — just flatness. Three possible explanations: (1) Specification and verification grow at the same rate, maintaining constant ratio — unlikely given 265 untested INVs. (2) Oscillation period exceeds 13 sessions — possible but not useful. (3) F(S) has a structural ceiling below theoretical maximum — most concerning. The likely explanation: each session adds ~10 specs and ~10 verifications, creating a pseudo-steady state. To break equilibrium and empirically test the saw-tooth model, the project needs a verification-only sprint (3-5 sessions, zero new specs). If F(S) rises to 0.75+ after the sprint, the saw-tooth is validated. If it stays at 0.62, the F(S) formulation may have anti-correlated components creating a structural maximum. This is a falsifiable prediction about the system's own convergence model. VERIFICATION: Execute verification sprint, measure F(S) before and after. Predicted outcome: F(S) rises to 0.72-0.78. If falsified: revise F(S) component weights or formulation. INTERACTS WITH: F(S) stagnation diagnosis (same underlying issue), verification sprint proposal (the intervention), structural ceiling risk (the alternative hypothesis). TRACES TO: ADR-FOUNDATION-014 (convergence thesis), ADR-FOUNDATION-020 (falsification-first).\n- ASSESSMENT RISK: Formalism Cost May Exceed Value — Risk 5. The project carries enormous formal overhead: 22 spec files, 83+ invariants with falsification conditions, 30+ ADR categories, 265 verification tasks, hypothesis ledger with 273 predictions, bilateral scans, fitness function with 7 weighted components, 8-type divergence taxonomy, 3 learning loops, trilateral coherence model, policy manifest. Each element is internally consistent and well-motivated from first principles. But the aggregate cost of maintaining this formalism — writing specs, verifying invariants, recording hypotheses, measuring F(S), running bilateral scans — may exceed the value it produces. Especially if the primary user is a single developer working with AI agents. Evidence: Sessions 036 and 028 spent significant time on administrative convergence (closing 136 tasks, 28 EPICs) rather than implementation. Issue management overhead competes with productive work. The formalism is designed to scale with team size and domain complexity — but for a solo effort, lighter-weight approaches (simple README-based tracking, git-based history) might produce comparable outcomes with less ceremony. MITIGATION: This is not a risk to eliminate but to monitor. The saw-tooth model is the diagnostic: if F(S) moves after the verification sprint, the formalism is earning its keep — the measurement apparatus is detecting real convergence. If F(S) doesn't move, the formalism may be measuring itself rather than reality. S0-CLOSE validation is the ultimate test: does all this formal machinery produce better outcomes than a simpler approach on external projects? VERIFICATION: Compare braid-managed external project outcomes to baseline (no braid, just git + notes). If braid scores significantly higher → formalism justified. If comparable → formalism overhead not earning its cost. INTERACTS WITH: S0-CLOSE proposal (ultimate value test), complexity acceleration risk (formalism is a contributor to LOC growth), scope creep (spec writing creates its own backlog). TRACES TO: ADR-FOUNDATION-014, C5 (traceability), C6 (falsifiability).\n- ASSESSMENT: The Deepest Question — Type 9 Divergence. Is the system observing its own failure to converge? The project's bedrock claim: it implements the atomic operation at every level (observe reality → compare to model → reduce the discrepancy). But the system's most important discrepancy — F(S) stagnant at 0.62 for 13 sessions, hypothesis ledger degrading, 265 untested INVs accumulating — is not being detected, diagnosed, or reduced by the system itself. A human reading the status dashboard sees these numbers. But the guidance system does not emit 'your verification pipeline is the bottleneck.' The routing function does not prioritize verification tasks over new feature tasks when the spec-impl gap is widening. The harvest does not capture 'F(S) has not moved in 5 sessions — this is anomalous.' If Braid is truly a learning system, it should detect its own stagnation as Type 9 divergence (Reflexive: system vs system's-model-of-itself) and recommend the verification sprint. If it cannot — if an external assessment must identify the obvious — then the self-improvement loop (the Y-combinator property) is not yet operational. THE TEST: Run braid status and braid seed --task 'improve convergence' and check whether the system recommends what this assessment recommends. If it does: the system is learning. If not: the most important invariant — the system can diagnose its own convergence failures — is untested and possibly violated. This is the only divergence type that matters at this stage. VERIFICATION: Implement Type 9 detection: an anomaly detector that fires when F(S) is flat for N sessions, or hypothesis mean error exceeds threshold, or untested INV count exceeds threshold. Wire into guidance footer as priority signal. TRACES TO: SEED.md §6 (8-type divergence taxonomy + Type 9), ADR-FOUNDATION-014, C7 (self-bootstrap).\n- ASSESSMENT RISK: Convergence Thesis Structural Ceiling — Risk 1. F(S) at 0.62 for 13 sessions may not be a verification bottleneck but the equilibrium point of the F(S) formulation itself. The 7-component weighted sum may asymptotically approach a value below 1.0 due to structural interdependencies between components. Specifically: improving V (validation) requires adding tests, which adds spec elements, which increases the denominator for C (coverage) and I (incompleteness). If these components are anti-correlated by construction — V improvement mechanically suppresses C and I — then F(S) has a structural maximum well below 1.0 regardless of verification effort. This would mean the convergence thesis (ADR-FOUNDATION-014) is unfalsifiable in its current form: F(S) → 1.0 may be mathematically impossible given the component formulation. MITIGATION: The verification sprint (Priority 2) empirically tests this. If F(S) doesn't move after 265 INVs are verified, the formulation needs revision. Possible fixes: (1) decouple component denominators, (2) use relative improvement rather than absolute scores, (3) normalize by phase-appropriate expectations. VERIFICATION: After verification sprint, if F(S) > 0.72 → risk mitigated (formulation works). If F(S) remains 0.60-0.65 → risk confirmed (structural ceiling). INTERACTS WITH: F(S) stagnation diagnosis, verification sprint proposal, saw-tooth validation. TRACES TO: ADR-FOUNDATION-014, ADR-FOUNDATION-020.\n\n**Next session task**: continue: Session 046: INQUIRY-ENGINE + PERF-REGRESSION audit + store repair\nRun: `braid seed --task \"continue: Session 046: INQUIRY-ENGINE + PERF-REGRESSION audit + store repair\"` to start the next session.\n" :op :assert}
