1754e01; What connects thinking about topology and coupling for ... to ADR-FOUNDATION-017: THE HYPOTHETICO-DEDUCTIVE LOOP. The complete ...?; Session entity: :task/t-d3673eb6; Session entity: :recon/trace-871d9545a2afd9aa; Session entity: :task/t-289499b3; Session entity: :recon/trace-e4b466ccd6fd0a49; Session entity: :recon/trace-b86ddfdea0293ee8; BETA_1 PROBLEM: compute_beta_1 is the ONE computation that cannot be incrementally maintained as a simple accumulator. It requires the full reference graph (entities connected by Ref-valued datoms) to compute the first Betti number (cycle count) via rank(kernel(Laplacian)). This is fundamentally O(E+V) where E=edges, V=vertices. However, the GRAPH ITSELF can be maintained incrementally: on each Ref-valued Assert, add an edge to an adjacency list. The beta_1 computation is then lazy-invalidated: a dirty flag is set on each graph mutation, and beta_1 is recomputed on read (not on write). With ~10K entities and ~5K Ref edges, beta_1 recomputation is O(V²) for eigendecomposition — feasible at ~100M ops, but potentially slow. Alternative: maintain a Union-Find (disjoint set) data structure incrementally. A new edge that connects two already-connected components doesn't change beta_1. An edge that creates a cycle increments beta_1 by 1. This gives O(α(n)) per edge insertion where α is the inverse Ackermann function — effectively O(1). The Union-Find approach is algebraically correct because beta_1 = |edges| - |vertices| + |components| (Euler characteristic for graphs). We maintain |edges|, |vertices|, and |components| as counters. |components| decrements by 1 each time Union-Find merges two sets. This makes beta_1 O(1) on read. ACCEPTANCE: beta_1 from incremental Union-Find == beta_1 from batch eigendecomposition for ALL test stores.; Session entity: :task/t-33287dff; Session entity: :recon/trace-ac9b60b6da93baf8; AUDIT F-ERR-003: Clippy fails CI gate with 8 errors — all trivial. PROBLEM: cargo clippy --all-targets -- -D warnin