d status.rs correctly use unwrap_or(Ordering::Equal). If any fitness component computes as NaN (e.g., 0/0 from empty store with spec_count=0), the bilateral command panics. JUSTIFICATION: The type system should make invalid states unrepresentable. f64 includes NaN in its domain — |f64| > |valid fitness scores|. OrderedFloat<f64> (already a dependency via ordered-float) or explicit NaN-checking at construction would eliminate this class of error at the type level. SOLUTION: Either (1) replace FitnessScore(f64) with FitnessScore(OrderedFloat<f64>), or (2) add .unwrap_or(Ordering::Equal) to the three unguarded call sites. Option 2 is faster; option 1 is more principled. VERIFICATION: FitnessScore(f64::NAN).partial_cmp(...) does not panic. DEPENDENCIES: Interacts with F-INV-002 (F(S) monotonicity) — both involve bilateral fitness computation. Independent fix. FILES: crates/braid-kernel/src/store.rs (FitnessDelta), crates/braid-kernel/src/bilateral.rs (FitnessComponents), crates/braid/src/commands/bilateral.rs:326,408,587. SEVERITY: Medium. WAVE: 0. EFFORT: 1h.; AUDIT ARCH-SOUNDNESS: Subsystem soundness classification — 9 SOUND, 8 UNSOUND-RECOVERABLE, 2 UNSOUND-STRUCTURAL, 2 UNTESTED. OBSERVATION: Full classification of 21 kernel subsystems: SOUND (31% of kernel LOC): Datom Model (741 LOC, types tight, Kani-verified), Query Engine (7,509 LOC, well-tested), Resolution (1,656 LOC, correct), Layout (1,264 LOC, clean EDN), Signal (1,465 LOC, epistemological), Deliberation (1,436 LOC, generic), Policy (1,471 LOC, the C8 solution), Topology (3,072 LOC, substrate-agnostic), Embedding (696 LOC, pure math). UNSOUND-RECOVERABLE (37%): Store Core (5,848 LOC — F-INV-001 LIVE view, F-TYPE-001 views isomorphism, F-INV-003 index sync), Schema (4,957 LOC — F-INV-004 hardcoded layers), Harvest (4,433 LOC — C8 in SpecCandidateType), Seed (5,314 LOC — C8 in directives), Bilateral (4,769 LOC — F-INV-002 false monotonicity), Coherence (1,300 LOC — Tier 2 C8), Concept (5,362 LOC — F-C8-005 innate concepts), Witness (2,226 LOC — C8 in completeness_guard). UNSOUND-STRUCTURAL (19%): Guidance (14,137 LOC — 17% of kernel, deeply DDIS-tied), Trilateral (2,048 LOC — hardcoded ISP). UNTESTED (6%): Merge cascade (1,518 LOC — 3/5 steps are no-ops), Compiler (3,072 LOC — generates tests never executed). SIGNIFICANCE: The 19% UNSOUND-STRUCTURAL subsystems are the critical finding — these cannot serve non-DDIS domains without redesign. The 37% UNSOUND-RECOVERABLE are all fixable within the current architecture. FILES: All kernel source files.; AUDIT ROADMAP: Six-wave implementation plan — 37 tasks, 264 hours total. WAVE 0 BLOCKING (17h, 6 tasks): W0-1 Fix 8 clippy errors (15m), W0-2 Guard NaN panics bilateral (30m), W0-3 Fix LIVE index retraction ordering (6h), W0-4 Add MaterializedViews isomorphism proptest (4h), W0-5 Unify index insertion paths (4h), W0-6 Investigate ignored stateright test (2h). Gate: CI green, no known correctness bugs. WAVE 1 SOUNDNESS (26h, 9 tasks): Attribute deser validation (1h), revise INV-BILATERAL-001 (3h), move INNATE_CONCEPTS to policy (2h), make witness C8-compliant (2h), make coherence Tier 2 C8-compliant (2h), investigate hypothesis degradation (8h), add dangling ref diagnostic (2h), reconcile INV counts (2h), batch-crystallize phantoms (4h). Gate: No UNSOUND-RECOVERABLE. WAVE 2 ARCHITECTURE (92h, 5 tasks): Move schema Layers 1-4 to policy (16h), make MaterializedViews configurable (12h), make trilateral configurable (8h), extract DDIS guidance to plugin (40h), implement merge cascade steps 2-4 (16h). Gate: No UNSOUND-STRUCTURAL, C8 compliant. WAVE 3 VERIFICATION (43h, 7 tasks): Coverage matrix (8h), STORE witnesses (12h), SCHEMA witnesses (6h), QUERY witnesses (8h), Kani LIVE harness (4h), Kani resolution harness (4h), namespace mapping doc (1h). Gate: 100% Stage 0 L2+. WAVE 4 PERFORMANCE (22h, 3 tasks): Incremental merge (6h), incremental cache (8h), profiling suite (8h). Gate: <2s status, <500ms merge. WAVE 5 PRODUCTION (64h, 7 tasks): Non-DDIS manifest (4h), E2E non-DDIS test (8h), access log significance (16h), confusion signal wiring (8h), compiler test execution (4h), failure modes to VERIFIED (16h), external docs (8h). Gate: Non-DDIS domain works E2E. CRITICAL PATH: W0->W1->W2->W5 = 199h (~5 weeks solo, ~2.5 weeks with 2 agents). W3 and W4 parallel with W1/W2.; PERF AUDIT FINDING P5-SEED-SCANS: seed.rs contains 15 separate store.datoms() full scans and 7 store.entities() calls. The assemble_seed function chains multiple O(N) passes for: active intentions, spec context, task context, verify_seed, and various helper functions. At 105K datoms, braid seed --inject AGENTS.md is one of the most expensive operations. Many of these scans collect overlapping information (e.g., spec entities, task entities, observation entities) that could be gathered in fewer passes. FIX: Refactor assemble_seed to use a single-pass collector that gathers all needed signals in one datoms() iteration, then distributes the collected data to the section builders. Similar to how StatusSnapshot computes everything once. This is a larger refactor than the others — seed touches many subsystems. Verification: braid seed output is byte-identical before/after refactor. Performance: measure wall-clock time, expect 5-10x improvement. Traces to ADR-STORE-006, INV-SEED-001. Depends on nothing, but benefits compound with P0-P3.; AUDIT ARCH-LOOPS: Loop analysis — 4 tight, 3 open, 2 broken, 2 phantom loops identified. OBSERVATION: TIGHT LOOPS (working): (1) Transact->LIVE->Query — datom inserted, LIVE updated, query reads current state. Healthy. (2) Observe->Store->Seed->Agent — knowledge captured, stored, assembled into seed for next session. The core hypothesis loop, working. (3) Hypothesis->Outcome->Calibration — prediction at harvest, actual at task close, mean error computed, weights adjusted. Working but degrading (mean error 0.521, trend degrading). (4) Bilateral Scan->Gap Detection->Task Creation — scans detect gaps, gaps surface as tasks, tasks completed. Working. OPEN LOOPS (data produced not consumed): (1) Compiler-generated proptests — compiler.rs generates test code but no pipeline executes it. NEG-010 violation. (2) 123 uncrystallized observations — captured but never promoted to spec elements. Pipeline stalls at crystallize step. (3) Merge cascade stubs — 3/5 steps are no-ops, merge receipt notes what should cascade but actions not implemented. BROKEN LOOPS (feedback path severed): (1) Access log significance — AS-007 specifies Hebbian significance via access log, budget module has ActivationStrategy types but access log not implemented. Queries happen, significance not accumulated. (2) Confusion signal -> re-ASSOCIATE — INV-SIGNAL-002 specifies confusion triggers re-association, signal types exist but pipeline not wired. PHANTOM LOOPS (appear closed, feedback is no-op): (1) F(S)->Guidance->Agent — F(S) computed and displayed but no automated response to changes. Agent sees number, no corrective action triggered. (2) Hypothesis calibration->weight adjustment — calibrate_boundary_weights() computes WeightAdjustment but adjusted weights not automatically transacted back. SIGNIFICANCE: 7 open/broken/phantom loops. NEG-010 says every loop must close. These are the system's current learning-loop debt.; AUDIT F-ERR-002: Error types use manual Display/Error impls — rationale is sound, document as ADR. PROBLEM: All error types use manual impl Display and impl Error instead of thiserror derives. This produces ~100 lines of boilerplate per error enum. The recovery_hint() pattern is unique and valuable — thiserror doesn't natively support per-variant recovery guidance. JUSTIFICATION: The kernel deliberately minimizes dependencies (#![forbid(unsafe_code)], no thiserror, no anyhow). The custom recovery_hint() method provides structured error guidance that aligns with NEG-INTERFACE-004 (No Error Without Recovery Hint). This is a principled design choice, not an oversight. The manual approach survives because error types are stable and rarely change. SOLUTION: Keep current approach. Document rationale as an ADR (e.g., ADR-INTERFACE-011: Manual Error Types with Recovery Hints). VERIFICATION: ADR written and indexed in docs/design/ADRS.md. DEPENDENCIES: None. This is an observation confirming existing design is correct. FILES: crates/braid-kernel/src/error.rs, crates/braid/src/error.rs. SEVERITY: Low. WAVE: 1. EFFORT: 30m.; AUDIT F-ARCH-003: CLI commands bootstrap.rs and trace.rs are application-layer DDIS-specific logic. PROBLEM: bootstrap.rs (1,046 LOC) parses spec/*.md files for INV/ADR/NEG patterns — DDIS-specific spec format parsing. trace.rs (1,464 LOC) scans Rust source files for INV-/ADR-/NEG- patterns — DDIS-specific traceability scanning. Both are methodology-specific and should eventually be application-layer plugins. However: they are in the CLI crate (braid), not the kernel (braid-kernel), so they don't violate the kernel/application boundary. They violate C8 for the overall system but not the kernel specifically. JUSTIFICATION: The layering is acceptable for Stage 0-1 where DDIS is the only policy. The CLI is expected to contain DDIS-specific commands. The proper long-term architecture: when the plugin/extractor framework matures, these become a braid-ddis plugin crate that the CLI loads dynamically. For now, keeping them in the CLI is the pragmatic choice. SOLUTION: When plugin framework exists, move to braid-ddis plugin crate. No action needed now. VERIFICATION: When moved, bootstrap.rs and trace.rs compile in a separate crate with only braid-kernel as dependency. DEPENDENCIES: Depends on future plugin framework (Wave 5 scope). Independent of kernel C8 fixes. FILES: crates/braid/src/bootstrap.rs, crates/braid/src/commands/trace.rs. SEVERITY: Medium. WAVE: 5. EFFORT: 8h.; Session entity: :task/t-474609fb; AUDIT F-INV-002 (CRITICAL): F(S) monotonicity claim is false — INV-BILATERAL-001 is falsified by normal operation. PROBLEM: INV-BILATERAL-001 states 'Monotonic Convergence — F(S) is non-decreasing under bilateral operations.' This claim is false. Counter-evidence from the project's own history: F(S) dropped from 0.67 to 0.58 in Session 033. More fundamentally: adding a spec element without implementation decreases coverage component; adding unresolved uncertainty decreases uncertainty component; discovering a contradiction decreases coherence component. F(S) is NOT monotone under bilateral operations — it is monotone under convergent bilateral operations (where both spec and impl grow together). JUSTIFICATION: From first principles, a fitness function over a partially-ordered domain is monotone only if every primitive operation preserves or increases fitness. OBSERVE and TRANSACT can add spec elements without impl, which increases spec_count while coverage_impl_targets stays constant, decreasing coverage ratio. The invariant conflates 'bilateral operations' (which include pure-spec additions) with 'convergent bilateral cycles' (which pair spec additions with impl additions). SOLUTION: (1) Revise INV-BILATERAL-001 to: 'F(S) is non-decreasing under the composition of a bilateral scan with its recommended resolution actions.' (2) Track F(S) with a high-water mark distinguishing expected temporary dips (new spec elements) from genuine regressions. VERIFICATION: The revised invariant is not falsified by adding a spec element without implementation. DEPENDENCIES: Affects hypothesis ledger calibration (R7) — code assuming monotonicity produces false alarms. Interacts with F-TYPE-001 (MaterializedViews accuracy) — both affect fitness-based decisions. FILES: crates/braid-kernel/src/bilateral.rs:1-50, spec/10-bilateral.md. SEVERITY: Critical. WAVE: 1. EFFORT: 3h.; AUDIT F-PERF-003: Binary cache invalidation on every transaction — CLI-mode performance regression. PROBLEM: Every write_tx() call marks the binary cache (store.bin) as stale. Cache rebuilt on next load_store(). For daemon mode this is fine (store in memory). For CLI mode (no daemon), every command writing a transaction triggers full cache rebuild on next read command. Session 032 documented: '30s braid status caused by RFL-2 txn per command invalidating all caches.' The daemon (Session 032 solution) amortizes this. JUSTIFICATION: The daemon architecture (ADR-STORE-006 revised) solves this for the primary use case. But CLI-mode fallback (when daemon isn't running) remains O(n) per read-after-write. This matters for CI pipelines and automated testing where the daemon may not be running. Incremental cache updates (append new datoms to binary cache rather than full invalidation) would make CLI-mode viable for larger stores. SOLUTION: Add incremental binary cache updates: serialize new datoms as a delta appended to store.bin. On load, read base + deltas. Compact periodically. VERIFICATION: CLI-mode 'braid status' after 'braid observe' takes <2s for 200K-datom store. DEPENDENCIES: Independent. Complements F-PERF-001 (merge performance). FILES: crates/braid/src/layout.rs (write_tx), live_store.rs. SEVERITY: Medium. WAVE: 4. EFFORT: 8h.; Session entity: :task/t-930fd19f; Session entity: :task/t-5fc73a07; AUDIT F-SPEC-003: 123 observations with uncrystallized spec IDs — open loop in observation-to-spec pipeline. PROBLEM: braid status methodology gaps report '123 observations with uncrystallized spec IDs -> braid spec create' and '28 tasks with unresolved spec refs -> crystallize first.' These are knowledge artifacts referencing non-existent spec elements — forward references to spec IDs that were never formalized. They represent an open loop: knowledge was captured (observe) but never promoted to formal spec elements (crystallize). JUSTIFICATION: NEG-010 (Do Not Open Loops) states every piece of information must feed back into the coherence model. Observations referencing phantom spec IDs are exactly this anti-pattern — data produced but not consumed by boundary evaluation. C5 (Traceability) requires every artifact to trace to a spec element. Phantom references violate this. SOLUTION: Batch-crystallize or prune. For each phantom reference: either (1) create the missing spec element via braid spec create, or (2) update the observation to remove the phantom reference. Run braid task search 'uncrystallized' to identify candidates. VERIFICATION: Methodology gap count drops to <20. DEPENDENCIES: Interacts with F-SPEC-002 (count discrepancy). Some of the 64-INV discrepancy may trace to these phantom references. FILES: braid status output, store observations. SEVERITY: Medium. WAVE: 1. EFFORT: 4h.; AUDIT METRICS-SNAPSHOT: Full codebase metrics at audit time (2026-03-26, commit 92bfb9a8). LOC: 117,661 total (83,293 kernel across 47 files + 34,368 CLI across 36 files). Tests: 2,043 passing, 0 failing, 1 ignored (transact_coherence_no_undetected_contradictions in stateright). Store: 108,627 datoms, 10,245 entities, 10,813 transactions. Spec: 433 elements (201 INVs, 156 ADRs, 69 NEGs) across 23 namespaces. F(S): 0.62. M(t): not reported. Hypothesis ledger: 145/273 completed, mean error 0.521, trend degrading. Trace: stale (55 files modified since last scan). Harvest: 293 tx since last — OVERDUE. Boundaries: spec<->impl 0.77 (142 gaps). Clippy: 8 errors (all trivial). unwrap(): 1,180 total (719 kernel + 461 CLI, ~90% in test code). Arc<Mutex>: 0. TODO/FIXME/HACK: 0. Crate attributes: #![forbid(unsafe_code)], #![deny(missing_docs)], #![deny(clippy::all)].; PERF AUDIT FINDING P6-INDEX-DUPLICATION: The Store type in store.rs has the same 20-line index maintenance block (insert to entity_index, attribute_index, vaet_index, avet_index, live_view) copy-pasted in 7+ locations: genesis(), from_datoms(), apply_datoms(), transact() (3 times for agent/user/tx metadata), merge(), inject_metadata_datom(). This creates risk of divergence — if a new index is added or behavior changes, all 7 sites must be updated. FIX: Extract a single fn insert_datom_to_indexes(&mut self, datom: &Datom) method on Store or MaterializedViews that handles all index updates for a single datom. Replace all 7 copy-paste sites with calls to this method. This is a pure refactoring with no behavioral change. Verification: all 2040 existing tests pass unchanged. No new tests needed — this is a code quality fix, not a feature. Traces to NEG-008 (no monolithic files — store.rs is 5,996 lines). Depends on nothing.; AUDIT F-ARCH-001: Guidance module is 17% of kernel LOC — god module risk. PROBLEM: The guidance system is 14,137 LOC across 4 files (guidance.rs 7,119 + context.rs 2,424 + routing.rs 2,879 + methodology.rs 1,715) — 17% of the 83,293 LOC kernel. By comparison, the core store is 5,848 LOC (7%). The guidance system is larger than store + schema + query + resolution combined. This suggests responsibility absorption: task routing could be a separate module, methodology scoring is a fitness variant, context assembly overlaps with seed.rs. JUSTIFICATION: ADR-STORE-015 (Free Functions Over Store Methods) established the principle that namespace operations should be independent modules. The guidance system violates this by accumulating routing, methodology, and context responsibilities into one mega-module. The god module anti-pattern makes changes risky (touching routing.rs might break methodology.rs) and makes C8 refactoring harder. SOLUTION: No immediate standalone action needed. When C8 refactoring happens (F-C8-004), the guidance split naturally produces: kernel-level guidance_framework (~3K LOC — budget-aware projection, context blocks, output modes) and policy-level ddis_guidance (~11K LOC — basin model, COTX routing, methodology scoring, DDIS-specific telemetry). VERIFICATION: Subsumed by F-C8-004 acceptance criteria. DEPENDENCIES: Subsumed by F-C8-004. The fix is the same work. FILES: crates/braid-kernel/src/guidance.rs, methodology.rs, routing.rs, context.rs. SEVERITY: Medium. WAVE: 2 (via F-C8-004). EFFORT: Included in F-C8-004 estimate.; PERF AUDIT FINDING P9-MAIN-DOUBLE-LOAD: main.rs opens a LiveStore TWICE per command invocation. Phase 1 (lines 108-131): opens LiveStore for session auto-detection, writes a session start transaction, drops it. Phase 3: opens ANOTHER LiveStore for post-command hooks (RFL-2 action prediction). Each LiveStore::open() deserializes the 92MB store.bin. This means every CLI invocation pays the deserialization cost twice. FIX: Open LiveStore once in main.rs, pass it through to the command dispatch. The session auto-detect and post-command hooks can use the same LiveStore handle. This requires threading the LiveStore through the command dispatch, which is a moderate refactor but eliminates a guaranteed 600ms overhead per command. Verification: only 1 LiveStore::open() call per CLI invocation (grep or debug logging). Performance: 300ms improvement per command. Traces to ADR-STORE-006, INV-STORE-021. Depends on nothing but benefits from P4 (daemon makes this irrelevant).; ASSESSMENT FINDING: Architectural Convergence Evidence — The architecture is converging, not accreting. 4 pieces of evidence: (1) Session 036 falsified the original 5-stage roadmap and replaced it with a 5-phase model. The system applied its own methodology to itself and corrected course — this IS the observe→compare→reduce loop working at the roadmap level. (2) Session 033 unified the convergence engine: MaterializedViews + project_delta + gradient routing compose cleanly. Three separate computation paths collapsed into one coherent pipeline. (3) The policy manifest (ADR-FOUNDATION-013) successfully separated substrate from application. policy.rs uses general-purpose boundary patterns — no DDIS-specific logic in kernel. (4) The extractor framework (Session 034) completed the plugin architecture with Layer 6 schema + meta-extractor. The growth pattern concern: Sessions 044-046 added Phase C/D features (concept engine, inquiry engine) while Phase B (S0-CLOSE) isn't complete. The inner loops (calibration, structure discovery) are being built before the outer loop (harvest/seed) is proven on external data. The architecture is sound but the sequencing is premature. TRACES TO: ADR-FOUNDATION-013 (policy manifest), ADR-FOUNDATION-014 (convergence thesis), C8 (substrate independence).; AUDIT F-SPEC-002: Spec element count discrepancy — 201 in spec files vs 265 in braid status. PROBLEM: Manual count of spec/*.md files yields 201 INVs. braid status reports '265 current-stage INVs untested' implying >265 INVs tracked in the store (108,627 datoms across 10,245 entities). The discrepancy of ~64 INVs suggests either: (1) spec elements created via 'braid spec create' that don't exist in spec/*.md files, or (2) the 'current-stage' filter includes elements from future stages. JUSTIFICATION: C7 (Self-Bootstrap) means the spec files and the store should be in correspondence. INV-BILATERAL-005 requires bilateral alignment between spec (as markdown) and implementation (as datoms). A 32% discrepancy between the two representations of the same specification is a structural divergence — exactly the kind of drift DDIS is designed to detect. SOLUTION: Run braid query '[:find (count ?e) :where [?e :spec/element-type \"invariant\"]]' to get exact store count. Reconcile with spec/*.md. Document any legitimate divergences (e.g., runtime-generated spec elements). VERIFICATION: Store INV count matches spec file count, or all discrepancies documented. DEPENDENCIES: Interacts with F-SPEC-003 (uncrystallized observations). Some discrepancies may be from the 123 observations with phantom spec IDs. FILES: spec/README.md, braid status output. SEVERITY: Medium. WAVE: 1. EFFORT: 2h.; ASSESSMENT FINDING: Scope Creep Pattern — Phase C/D work while Phase B incomplete. Sessions 044-046 added concept engine (198 KB new code), inquiry engine (emergent concepts + discrepancy steering + situational brief), online calibration (Otsu algorithm, per-observation threshold adjustment), and PERF-REGRESSION epic (16 tasks from architecture audit). None of this closes the S0-CLOSE epic or addresses the three known critical issues: (1) open calibration loop, (2) coverage validation bug, (3) 265 untested INVs. The concept engine work is particularly concerning: 3 sessions spent on a feature that demonstrably doesn't work (concept collapse persists, 4.1/10 score) while the calibration pipeline (which DOES work when outcomes are recorded) was left broken. Issue inflation also visible: 883 total issues, 70 open across 8+ epics spanning 4 phases. The backlog has become a second project to manage. Sessions 036 and 028 spent significant time on administrative convergence (closing 136 tasks, 28 EPICs) rather than implementation — a sign that issue management overhead is competing with productive work. VERIFICATION: Track ratio of issues-created-per-session vs issues-closed-per-session. Healthy: close > create. Current: create ≈ close (steady-state backlog). After resequencing: close >> create for 3-5 sessions (verification sprint). INTERACTS WITH: Premature intelligence finding (same root cause), velocity stall (possible consequence of scope diffusion), S0-CLOSE proposal (the corrective). TRACES TO: NEG-010 (no open loops), ADR-FOUNDATION-014.; AUDIT F-TYPE-002: Value::Ref admits unvalidated reference cycles. PROBLEM: Value::Ref(EntityId) allows any EntityId as a reference target including entities that do not exist in the store. Schema validation (validate_datom) checks value types but does not verify referential integrity at transact time. No mechanism exists to detect permanently dangling references. JUSTIFICATION: This is intentional for eventual consistency — C4 (CRDT merge by set union) means references may precede referents in a multi-agent scenario. The design correctly separates write-time flexibility from read-time verification. However, the absence of any diagnostic for permanently dangling references violates the completeness principle: every data quality concern should have a detection mechanism. SOLUTION: Add store.dangl