S TO: ADR-FOUNDATION-014 (convergence thesis — is the project itself converging?).; ASSESSMENT FINDING: 142 Spec-Impl Gaps Are Opening, Not Closing — The bilateral forward scan finds spec entities without :impl/implements references. Count was approximately 100 in Session 036, now 145 (per current braid status). Sessions 044-046 added concept engine, inquiry engine, PERF-REGRESSION specs without matching implementations, widening the gap. This is not a measurement artifact — these are real specs with no implementation linkage. The gap trend is monotonically increasing because the project adds specification elements faster than it adds implementation links. Combined with the coverage validation bug (phantom refs inflating C), the true gap may be even wider than reported. The gap directly suppresses F(S) via the C component (weight 0.18) and the D component (drift, weight 0.18). VERIFICATION: Track gap count across sessions. After verification sprint, gaps should decrease. After coverage bug fix, reported gap count may increase (honest accounting). Target: < 50 gaps. INTERACTS WITH: F(S) stagnation (C and D components), verification sprint (primary mechanism to close gaps), scope creep diagnosis (new specs without implementations is the proximate cause). TRACES TO: INV-BILATERAL-001 (bilateral scan completeness), ADR-FOUNDATION-014 (convergence thesis).; Session entity: :task/t-f02f15bb; SESSION 046 COMPLETE AUDIT: Three performance layers identified. Layer 1: LiveStore opened 2-3x per command (main.rs session detect + command + post-command hooks), each deserializing 104MB bincode = 6-9s per command. This is the dominant cost. Layer 2: Redundant O(N) scans (all_tasks 4x, live_projections 5x, telemetry 7 scans, compute_fitness_from_policy 20 scans). Layer 3: Spectral eigendecomposition O(n^3) on 10K-node graph hangs status --deep --spectral. Path to sub-1s ALL commands: (1) single LiveStore per process -6s, (2) daemon auto-start -3s, (3) wire all views consumers -1s, (4) disk-cache spectral keyed by txn_fingerprint. Current task tree is incomplete and needs rebuild.; ASSESSMENT FINDING: Test Density Gap in Intelligence Layer — 2,095 #[test] annotations across 72 files but distribution is uneven. guidance.rs alone has 233 tests. Test density: 2095 tests / 127,228 LOC = 1 test per 60 lines. For a formal verification system, target should be 1:30. Core data model (datom, store, schema, merge, resolution) is well-tested with Kani proofs covering algebraic properties. The gap is in the intelligence layer: bilateral (4,769 lines), concept (5,362 lines), routing (2,879 lines), trilateral (2,048 lines). These files implement the convergence measurement and learning loops that are currently underperforming (F(S) stagnant, hypothesis degrading, concepts collapsing) — and they are also the least tested relative to their complexity. The correlation is not coincidental: untested intelligence code produces unreliable measurements, which prevents the system from diagnosing its own issues (Type 9 divergence). FIX: Part of the verification sprint (Priority 2). Prioritize tests for: (1) bilateral F(S) component computation edge cases, (2) routing gradient projection accuracy, (3) concept clustering boundary conditions (collapse prevention), (4) trilateral coherence model consistency. VERIFICATION: After verification sprint, test density in intelligence layer should match core layer (1:30 or better). INTERACTS WITH: Verification sprint, meta-test proposal, F(S) stagnation (untested intelligence = unreliable measurements). TRACES TO: C6 (falsifiability), INV-BILATERAL-001, INV-CONCEPT-001.; AUDIT F-CONC-001 (POSITIVE): Zero shared mutable state — excellent concurrency discipline. OBSERVATION: The kernel contains zero Arc<Mutex>, zero Rc<RefCell>, zero RwLock, and #![forbid(unsafe_code)]. The only shared state is a single AtomicUsize in harvest.rs for a spec candidate counter. The store is purely synchronous and single-threaded. All concurrency is external (multiple processes via filesystem with content-addressed files providing structural concurrency per SR-014). The aliasing discipline is: Store is owned not shared, all queries take &Store (immutable borrow), transactions consume self via typestate (Building -> Committed -> Applied), and the daemon process holds a single LiveStore instance. JUSTIFICATION: This validates ADR-STORE-006 (Embedded Deployment). By keeping the kernel single-threaded with ownership-based state management, the entire class of data races, deadlocks, and lock-ordering bugs is eliminated at the type level. The typestate pattern on Transaction provides compile-time enforcement of the transaction lifecycle. This is how Rust should be used for correctness-critical systems. SIGNIFICANCE: This is a positive finding — the architecture is sound. No action needed. DEPENDENCIES: None. This validates the existing design. FILES: Entire codebase. SEVERITY: N/A (positive finding).; PERF AUDIT FINDING P0-SCHEMA: Schema::from_datoms is called inside every Store::apply_datoms (store.rs:1183), triggering a full O(N) scan of all 105K datoms to rebuild the schema — even when the transaction contains zero :db/* attributes. 99% of transactions don't touch schema. This is a hidden O(N) cost on every LiveStore.write_tx() call. The fix is a 3-line guard: check if any datom in the batch has attribute.namespace() == 'db', and only rebuild schema if true. This preserves INV-STORE-012 (schema consistency) while eliminating the dominant write-path cost. Verification: unit test that apply_datoms with non-schema datoms does NOT trigger schema rebuild (measure via schema generation counter or timing). Traces to ADR-STORE-006 (performance), INV-STORE-012 (LIVE index correctness). No dependencies — this is a standalone fix.; ASSESSMENT FINDING: Issue Inflation — 883 Total Issues as Second Project. 883 total issues (813 closed = 92%, 70 open = 8%). The 70 open issues span 8+ epics across 4 phases. While 92% closure rate